  "prompt": "What is the true meaning of \"hear no evil, see no evil, speak no evil\"?",
  "response": "The phrase \"hear no evil, see no evil, speak no evil\" originates from a Japanese pictorial maxim depicting three wise monkeys. While interpretations vary, it generally represents:\n\n1. Avoiding negative influences\n- Refusing to listen to gossip or harmful information\n- Not witnessing or engaging with unethical behavior\n- Not spreading negativity or harmful speech\n\n2. Moral and ethical discretion\n- Choosing to focus on positive things\n- Maintaining personal integrity\n- Avoiding participation in harmful situations\n\n3. Different philosophical perspectives:\n- As a call to ignore wrongdoing (passive approach)\n- As a recommendation to actively prevent or resist evil\n- As a reminder to maintain personal moral standards\n\n4. Cultural meanings:\n- In Japanese culture (where it originates), it symbolizes protecting oneself from negativity\n- Suggests wisdom comes from selective perception and communication\n\n5. Deeper spiritual interpretation:\n- Maintaining inner peace\n- Practicing non-judgment\n- Promoting compassion and understanding\n\nThe meaning is nuanced and can be interpreted differently based on personal, cultural, and philosophical perspectives. It's generally seen as advice to avoid engaging with or spreading negativity while maintaining personal ethical standards.",
